MNIST Card Data

We compare the methods used with our methods with a more standard dataset used in this paper Mukhoti, J., Kirsch, A., van Amersfoort, J., Torr, P. H. S., & Gal, Y. (2021). Deterministic Neural Networks with Appropriate Inductive Biases Capture Epistemic and Aleatoric Uncertainty. http://arxiv.org/abs/2102.11582.

We used

  • MNIST: Handwritten digits from 0 to 9 as in-ditribution and training images;
  • AmbiguousMNIST: Ambiguous handwritten digits, as ambiguous data;
  • FashionMNSIT: Clothes images within the same format as novel data;

Data analysis in the feature space

To speed up the training and enable interactive and incremental training during the user study, we had to perform transfer learning. To do so, we investigated embeddings that transform our data into a feature space.

We investigate three different embeedings:

  • MobileNetV1,
  • MobileNetV2,
  • ResNet50,

Of course, it seems useless to use such embeddings with MNIST images that are 28x28 pixels. Indeed, the ResNet50 pre-logit layer output is larger than the initial image. However, for the sake of the comparison with our playing card data, we still use these embeddings for the benchamrk. We also resample the image to have 32x32 pixels, that is the minimum size for the embeddings to be able to process the data.

To better estimate the richness and the variance distribution within the feature spaces, we perform Principal Component Analysis (PCA).

In[129]:
var = Figures.scree_plot(z_train, z_test, z_uncertain)

We compute the Shannon entropy using the 10 first eigen-values of the Principal Analysis decomposition.

In[136]:
import scipy
names = ["MobileNetV1", "MobileNetV2", "ResNet50", "MobileNetV1+MobileNetV2", "All embeddings concatenated"]
for i in range(len(var)):
    print(names[i], " : ", scipy.stats.entropy(var[i]))

MobileNetV1  :  1.7227495
MobileNetV2  :  1.6930317
ResNet50  :  1.9929383
MobileNetV1+MobileNetV2  :  1.9773712
All embeddings concatenated  :  1.993009

Observation: Depending on the embedding, the variance in the data is more or less distributed among the principal components:

  • The variance is very concentrated on a single component for MobileNetV1 and V2
  • In the opposite, the variance is more distributed among the components for ResNet50

The Shannon entropy on the 10 first eigen values of the PCA is a good indicator of the variance distribution among the components. We might expect better separation between uncertain and certain data with ResNet50 since the variance is more distributed across several dimension.

Let's vizualize the feature space for these two embeedings.

In[137]:
embeddings: dict = {0: "MobileNetV1", 1: "MobileNetV2", 2: "ResNet50", 3: "[MobileNetV1 + MobileNetV2]", 4: "All embeddings"}
z_all = np.concatenate((z_train, z_test, z_uncertain), axis = 0)
all_data = pd.concat([train, test, uncertain])
image_all = list(all_data["X_PIL"].values)
for i in [0,1,2]:
    z =Data.select_embedding(z_all, i)
    pca = PCA(n_components=10, svd_solver='full')
    z_all_2D = pca.fit(z).transform(z)
    plt.figure(figsize=(30,15))
    for j in range(len(image_all)):
        Figures.imscatter(z_all_2D[:,0][j], z_all_2D[:,1][j], image_all[j], ax=None, zoom=1.2)
        plt.title("Data in the feature space of the {0} embedding".format(embeddings[i]))

Observations: The separation between the different type of ambiguity seems more coherent within the ResNet50 embedding.
